Knowledge, attitudes and perceptions about CHIKV, mosquito-borne diseases and their prevention were investigated in 46/2326 (2%) cross-sectional articles; 
 Table 1. Articles on attitudes and perceptions to chikungunya disease focused on concerns about toxic or environmental effects of chemical control measures (3/46; 7%), perception about the severity and risks associated with chikungunya disease (16/46; 35%), and perception on the efficacy of various protective measures (13/46; 28%). Several studies evaluated knowledge on chikungunya disease (29/46; 63%), CHIKV vectors (27/46; 59%) and behavioral mitigation practices for CHIKV (33/46; 72%). A single study examined willingness to pay for protection against CHIKV [
 268].
